        <div class="text-center">
          <h3>Quick Sort</h3>
        </div>
        
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 1 — What is Quick Sort?

            Quick Sort is a **divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm**.

            It works by:

            1. Selecting a **pivot** element
            2. **Partitioning** the array into two groups  
              - Elements **less than** the pivot  
              - Elements **greater than** the pivot
            3. Recursively applying the same process.

            Example array:

            `[9, 3, 7, 1, 6, 2]`

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Unsorted Array]-->B[Choose Pivot];
              B-->C[Partition Array];
              C-->D[Recursively Sort Left];
              C-->E[Recursively Sort Right];
              D-->F[Sorted Array];
              E-->F;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 2 — Divide and Conquer

            Quick Sort follows the **divide-and-conquer paradigm**.

            Steps:

            1. **Divide** the array into two partitions
            2. **Conquer** by recursively sorting the partitions
            3. **Combine** (no explicit merge needed)

            Unlike merge sort, Quick Sort sorts **in place**.

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Array]-->B[Left Partition];
              A-->C[Right Partition];
              B-->D[Sorted Left];
              C-->E[Sorted Right];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 3 — Choosing a Pivot

            The **pivot** is the element used to divide the array.

            Common pivot choices:

            - First element
            - Last element
            - Middle element
            - Random element

            Example:

            `[9, 3, 7, 1, 6, 2]`

            Choose pivot = **7**

            Partition result:

            `[3,1,6,2] 7 [9]`

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Array]-->B[Choose Pivot 7];
              B-->C[Elements < 7];
              B-->D[Elements > 7];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 4 — Partitioning

            Partitioning rearranges elements so that:

            - Left side < pivot
            - Right side > pivot

            Example:

            `[9, 3, 7, 1, 6, 2]`

            Pivot = 7

            After partition:

            `[3,1,6,2] 7 [9]`

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[9 3 7 1 6 2]-->B[Partition];
              B-->C[3 1 6 2];
              B-->D[7];
              B-->E[9];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 5 — Recursive Sorting

            Quick Sort **recursively sorts** the two partitions.

            Example:

            `[3,1,6,2] 7 [9]`

            Sort left partition:

            `[3,1,6,2]`

            Sort right partition:

            `[9]`

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[3 1 6 2]-->B[Choose Pivot];
              B-->C[Partition];
              C-->D[Recursive Calls];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 6 — Base Case

            Recursion stops when:

            - The array has **0 or 1 element**

            These arrays are already sorted.

            Example:

            `[9]`

            No further work needed.

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Single Element]-->B[Already Sorted];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 7 — Quick Sort Pseudocode

            Simplified pseudocode:

            ```
            quickSort(arr):
              if length(arr) <= 1
              return arr

              pivot = choosePivot(arr)

              left = elements < pivot
              right = elements > pivot

              return quickSort(left) + pivot + quickSort(right)
            ```

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[quickSort]-->B[Choose Pivot];
              B-->C[Partition];
              C-->D[Sort Left];
              C-->E[Sort Right];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 8 — Time Complexity

            Quick Sort has different time complexities:

            Best case:

            ####O(n log n)####

            Average case:

            ####O(n log n)####

            Worst case:

            ####O(n^2)####

            Worst case occurs when partitions are very **unbalanced**.

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Balanced Partition]-->B[O n log n];
              C[Unbalanced Partition]-->D[O n^2];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 9 — Advantages of Quick Sort

            Advantages:

            - Very **fast in practice**
            - **In-place sorting**
            - Excellent **cache performance**
            - Widely used in real systems

            Many programming languages use Quick Sort internally.

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Quick Sort]-->B[Fast];
              A-->C[In-place];
              A-->D[Efficient];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 10 — Summary

            Quick Sort algorithm:

            1. Choose a **pivot**
            2. **Partition** the array
            3. **Recursively sort** partitions
            4. Stop when partitions have **1 element**

            Final example:

            `[9,3,7,1,6,2]`

            Sorted result:

            `[1,2,3,6,7,9]`

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Unsorted]-->B[Partition];
              B-->C[Recursive Sorting];
              C-->D[Sorted Array];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise — Implement Quick Sort

            In this exercise you will implement the **Quick Sort algorithm**.

            Quick Sort is a **divide-and-conquer algorithm** that sorts an array by:

            1. Choosing a **pivot**
            2. **Partitioning** the array
            3. Recursively sorting the partitions

            Your goal is to write a Python function:

            quick_sort(arr)

            that returns the sorted array.

            Example input:

            `[9, 3, 7, 1, 6, 2]`

            Expected output:

            `[1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 9]`

            ---

            ## Steps to Implement Quick Sort

            Follow these steps:

            1. **Define the base case**

            If the array length is **0 or 1**, it is already sorted.

            2. **Choose a pivot**

            Select one element of the array as the pivot.  
            For this exercise, use the **last element**.

            3. **Partition the array**

            Create two lists:

            - elements **less than or equal to** the pivot
            - elements **greater than** the pivot

            4. **Recursively sort the partitions**

            Call quick sort on both partitions.

            5. **Combine the results**

            Concatenate:

            left + pivot + right

            ---

            ## Algorithm Visualization

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Array]-->B[Choose Pivot];
              B-->C[Partition Array];
              C-->D[Left Subarray];
              C-->E[Right Subarray];
              D-->F[Recursive Sort];
              E-->G[Recursive Sort];
              F-->H[Sorted Array];
              G-->H;
            /mermaid

            ---

            ## Your Task

            Implement the function:

            quick_sort(arr)

            Requirements:

            - Use **recursion**
            - Use **list comprehensions** if possible
            - Return a **new sorted list**

            Test your implementation with different arrays.

            ---

            spoiler
            ```
            def quick_sort(arr):
                if len(arr) <= 1:
                    return arr

                # Choose pivot
                pivot = arr[-1]

                # Partition
                left = [x for x in arr[:-1] if x <= pivot]
                right = [x for x in arr[:-1] if x > pivot]

                # Recursive sorting
                return quick_sort(left) + [pivot] + quick_sort(right)

            /spoiler
            ```
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

